TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Theory of Conservatism
AU  - Li, Hao
Y1  - 2001/06/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/321018
DO  - 10.1086/321018
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 617
EP  - 636
VL  - 109
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - A free?rider problem arises when a group choice between two alternatives has to be made on the basis of privately collected evidence, leading to insufficient effort in gathering evidence and an ex ante welfare loss for the group. To alleviate the free?rider problem, the group can commit to a ?conservative? rule, whereby the decision is made against the alternative favored by the group?s preference or prior when evidence supports it but is not preponderant. Optimal conservatism increases private incentives to gather evidence and improves the quality of the group decision. My result explains why sometimes groups appear overly cautious toward favored alternatives.
AB  - A free?rider problem arises when a group choice between two alternatives has to be made on the basis of privately collected evidence, leading to insufficient effort in gathering evidence and an ex ante welfare loss for the group. To alleviate the free?rider problem, the group can commit to a ?conservative? rule, whereby the decision is made against the alternative favored by the group?s preference or prior when evidence supports it but is not preponderant. Optimal conservatism increases private incentives to gather evidence and improves the quality of the group decision. My result explains why sometimes groups appear overly cautious toward favored alternatives.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/321018
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/321018
Y2  - 2024/03/19
